<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900511-0054</DOCNO><DOCID>900511-0054.</DOCID><HL>   Merger of Conwest,   Mineral Resources,   And Barons Approved</HL><DATE>05/11/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CEX.B T.MRI T.BN</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   TORONTO -- Conwest Exploration Co., Mineral ResourcesInternational Ltd. and Barons Oil Ltd. said theirshareholders approved the merger of the three companies.   Under terms of the merger, Conwest, a Toronto-based oil,gas and mining concern, will issue new Class B subordinatevoting shares to minority holders of both subsidiaries.Conwest owns 51% of Mineral Resources, a mining concern.Toronto-based Mineral Resources owns 85% of Barons, an oiland gas production company based in Calgary, Alberta.</LP><TEXT>   The new company will retain the name Conwest ExplorationCo. The merger is expected to take effect June 1.   Separately, John Lamacraft, Conwest's president and chiefexecutive officer, said he expects operating income this yearof 65.5 million Canadian dollars ($56.2 million) on revenueof C$122.1 million, up from last year's operating income ofC$56.6 million and revenue of C$103.2 million. Operatingincome is figured before taxes, depreciation, interest costsand minority interest payments.   Mr. Lamacraft, speaking at the company's annual meeting,said the gains will come largely from increased production ofoil and natural gas, following several recent acquisitions.   In yesterday's trading on the Toronto Stock Exchange,Conwest Class B shares closed at 12.75 Canadian dollars($10.94), up 37.5 cents. Mineral Resources shares rose 37.5cents, to C$5.50; and Barons shares gained 15 cents, to closeat C$2.90.</TEXT></DOC>